nations of their birth. Considering migration and settlement as complex, interrelated processes that inform each other across multiple generations and geographies, Andrea Katherine Medovarski challenges the gendered constructions of nationhood and diaspora with a particular focus on Canadian and British black women writers, including Dionne Brand, Esi Edugyan, and Zadie Smith. Re-evaluating gender and spatial relations, Settling Down and Settling Up argues that local experiences, often conceptualized through the language of the feminine and the domestic in black women’s writings, are no less important than travel and border crossings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCanadian literaturexBlack authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aChildren of immigrantszCanadaxIntellectual life. 0aChildren of immigrantszGreat BritainxIntellectual life. 0aEnglish literaturexBlack authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aIdentity (Psychology) in literature. 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh  aBlack British literature.  aBlack Canadian literature.  ablack diaspora.  achildren of immigrants.  acritical multiculturalism.  acultural studies.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary studies.  asecond generation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268533840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442685338423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442685338.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles